  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "As of `v1.11`, only the recipient of funds can trigger a withdrawal in `PullPayments`: \r\n\r\n```\r\nfunction withdrawPayments() public {\r\n  address payee = msg.sender;\r\n  escrow.withdraw(payee);\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe same thing happens in `SplitPayment`:\r\n```\r\nfunction claim() public {\r\n  address payee = msg.sender;\r\n  ...\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis means interactions from contracts with these interfaces are limited, since a) they won't be able to receive their funds (unless the respective function call is coded into them), and most importantly b) they won't be able to trigger transactions for another recipient (e.g. have a contract schedule pull payments and another one then execute them in sequence, abstracting the whole thing away from end users).\r\n\r\nI think all of these functions should provide an `address recipient` parameter, and `msg.sender` should never be used for this purpose (and only to determine origin, e.g. when doing access control).",
